Raw dev notes -- RAG Pipeline: The Daily Grind of Data Syncing

Okay, so the big picture here is the RAG Knowledge Base Pipeline. The whole point of this thing is to build a smart system that can answer questions using *our* specific internal knowledge, not just whatever an LLM scraped from the internet. It's about making sure our AI tools are grounded in truth, our truth. This particular part of the pipeline is all about getting that knowledge *into* the system, specifically Q&A pairs from one of our key internal sources.

This past week has been pretty focused on just watching the data flow. The commits are all `sync: X new Q&A from ***.net`. It's been a steady stream, day after day, pulling in new Q&A content. We're seeing anywhere from 1 to 10 new Q&A items getting ingested daily. It's a good sign that the automated sync process is actually working and picking up new content as it appears on the source site. The "0 new posts" is interesting – it means for this period, all the new content was Q&A, which is fine, but it's a mental note that the "posts" part of the sync might need attention later, or maybe there just weren't any new posts to sync. For now, the Q&A ingestion is the win.

What was hard or surprising? Honestly, getting to this point where it's just *running* consistently was the real beast. The commits just show the successful syncs, but they don't show the headaches of setting up the initial data extraction, figuring out the parsing logic, mapping the schema, and making sure we handle duplicates gracefully. There's always that nagging doubt: is the data *actually* good? Is it formatted correctly for the RAG system downstream? It's one thing to pull text, another to pull *useful* text. And the variability in daily volume (1 Q&A vs. 10 Q&A) means the system needs to be robust enough to handle those fluctuations without choking. It's a constant battle against "garbage in, garbage out." I'm also still thinking about how to better monitor this beyond just looking at commit messages – what if it *fails* silently?

It feels good, though, seeing the pipeline actually doing its job. It's a quiet kind of satisfaction, like watching a well-oiled machine hum along. It reinforces how critical robust data pipelines are for any AI application. You can have the fanciest LLM in the world, but if its knowledge base is stale or incomplete, it's useless. This whole process has been a good reminder that the "boring" data engineering work is often the most foundational and important. It's less about the flashy AI and more about the plumbing that makes it all possible.

Next up: Start looking at the actual retrieval performance of the RAG system with this new data.
